                  >
                    <span class="font-medium">What is WACC?</span>
                    <span
                      class="ml-4 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-90 transition-transform"
                      >&#9656;</span
                    >
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    WACC (weighted average cost of capital) is the blended rate
                    of return that a company must earn on its invested capital
                    to satisfy equity investors and debt holders. It weights the
                    cost of equity and after‑tax cost of debt by their
                    proportions in the firm’s capital structure.
                  </p>
                </details>

                <details class="p-4 group">
                  <summary
                    class="flex justify-between items-center cursor-pointer"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium">What is a good WACC value?</span>
                    <span
                      class="ml-4 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-90 transition-transform"
                      >&#9656;</span
                    >
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    There is no universal “good” WACC. Lower WACC means cheaper
                    capital and higher project values, but it must be consistent
                    with the company’s risk. Stable utilities often have WACC in
                    the mid‑single digits, while early‑stage or highly cyclical
                    companies can have double‑digit WACC.
                  </p>
                </details>

                <details class="p-4 group">
                  <summary
                    class="flex justify-between items-center cursor-pointer"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >Should I use market or book values in WACC?</span
                    >
                    <span
                      class="ml-4 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-90 transition-transform"
                      >&#9656;</span
                    >
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    For valuation and capital budgeting, you should use
                    <strong>market values</strong> of equity and debt, because
                    WACC is meant to reflect the current opportunity cost of
                    capital. Book values are based on historical costs and can
                    be very different from economic reality.
                  </p>
                </details>

                <details class="p-4 group">
                  <summary
                    class="flex justify-between items-center cursor-pointer"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >How do I estimate the cost of equity?</span
                    >
                    <span
                      class="ml-4 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-90 transition-transform"
                      >&#9656;</span
                    >
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The most common approach is the CAPM:
                    <em
                      >Cost of Equity = Risk‑Free Rate + Beta × Equity Risk
                      Premium</em
                    >. You can estimate beta from regression or use industry
                    betas, and take the equity risk premium from historical data
                    or market‑implied estimates.
                  </p>
                </details>

                <details class="p-4 group">
                  <summary
                    class="flex justify-between items-center cursor-pointer"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >Why is the cost of debt adjusted for taxes?</span
                    >
                    <span
                      class="ml-4 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-90 transition-transform"
                      >&#9656;</span
                    >
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Interest expense is usually tax‑deductible, which creates a
                    tax shield: the company pays less tax because it has debt.
                    The effective cost of debt is therefore the nominal rate
                    multiplied by (1 − tax rate), which is why WACC uses \(r_d(1
                    - T)\).
                  </p>
                </details>
